eblesshire, Scotland","Culbrynnie,Iverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Inverness-shire":"Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bisset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Bissett  .","French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>bisse</i> ‘fine linen’ (see   Bisson  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Bissett","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>biset</i> ‘dark’, a diminutive of <i>bis</i> (see   Biss  ).","Altered form of French <b>Bizet</b>: nickname for someone with a dark complexion, derived from <i>bis</i> ‘grayish-brown’. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>. Compare   Bissette  .","History: The surname <i>Bissett</i> (see 1 above) was brought to Scotland from Nottinghamshire <i>c.</i> 1175 by Henricus Byset, an Englishman who became a retainer of King William the Lion. — It was Jean George Bizet from Haute-Saône, France, whose surname was changed to <i>Bissett</i> (see 2 above) after his immigration to NS, Canada, in 1752."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Bisset Lord of Lovat was born in 1190, in Beauly, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Baron John Bisset 1st Lord of Lovat, was 26 and his mother, Leona Fitzwilliam Stewart, was 29. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Ermengarde Durward. He died in 1259, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 69, and was buried in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1190–1259":"1190–1259","1233–Female":"1233–Surnud","1235–Female":"1